attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, version 1 (ARM), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a malicious Linux botnet agent, specifically a variant of the Mirai or Gafgyt families targeting ARM-based IoT devices. Analysis reveals a high-confidence indicator of malicious intent: a string decryption routine (sub_10560) that de-obfuscates command-and-control (C2) strings and protocol headers from encrypted templates. The binary registers multiple modular attack vectors (DDoS) in function sub_8650, including HTTP flood capabilities (sub_bf44 constructng 'GET / HTTP/1.2' requests). It communicates with a hardcoded C2 server at 78.142.18.92 (found in sub_ecb4 and sub_ddc0). Further malicious traits include output suppression via /dev/null, custom PRNG for packet randomization, and complex socket-level state machine logic for maintaining a persistent connection to the C2.
